Reasoning: The paper investigates how peer effects operate in a real work setting, specifically in the context of an online labor market. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, which focuses on the design, evaluation, and implementation of interactive computing systems for human use. Additionally, the paper involves the use of field experiments, which may fall under the sub-category of Cybernetics (cs.CY), which deals with the study of communication and control processes in complex systems. The paper also involves the evaluation of work product, which may fall under the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), which focuses on the analysis and modeling of social and information networks. The paper also involves the measurement of productivity and the analysis of data, which may fall under the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG), which deals with the development of algorithms and models that enable computers to learn from data. Finally, the paper involves the evaluation of worker compliance with employer expectations, which may fall under the sub-category of Information Retrieval (cs.IR), which focuses on the retrieval of information from large collections of data.
